In this proclamation, President Barack Obama recognizes World AIDS Day and reaffirms the commitment of the United States to fight against HIV/AIDS. He mentions the National HIV/AIDS Strategy, which aims to reduce new infections, increase access to care, and reduce health disparities. The Affordable Care Act is also mentioned, as it expands access to HIV testing and healthcare for all Americans. The President emphasizes the importance of focusing on populations with the highest disparities, such as gay men and African American and Latino communities. He also highlights the progress made through the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) and the goal of achieving an AIDS-free generation. The proclamation calls for a shared responsibility in the fight against HIV/AIDS, involving partner countries, donors, civil society, and various organizations. The President urges the American people to remember those who have lost their lives to AIDS and support those living with the disease. The proclamation concludes by officially declaring December 1, 2012, as World AIDS Day.